keywords: ["Bioacoustics", "Humpback Whales", "Megaptera novaeangliae", "Song Evolution", "South Pacific"]
abstract: |
  Humpback whale songs are known for their complexity and rapid cultural 
  evolution. This study analyzes acoustic parameters of songs recorded across 
  three distinct breeding grounds in the South Pacific over a five-year period. 
  We identify significant differences in phrase duration and frequency range 
  between eastern and western populations, suggesting limited acoustic 
  exchange between these regions.
