::section{#introduction}
::meta
type: introduction
summary: "Overview of humpback whale song structure and the phenomenon of cultural transmission."
::

# Introduction

Humpback whales (*Megaptera novaeangliae*) produce complex, stereotyped 
sequences of vocalizations known as "songs" @cite{payne1971}. These songs 
evolve rapidly, with all males in a population typically singing the 
same version at any given time @cite{garland2011}.

This study aims to characterize the regional differences in song parameters 
within the South Pacific breeding grounds.

::endsection


::section{#methods}
::meta
type: methods
summary: "Data collection methods using passive acoustic monitoring (PAM) and song analysis parameters."
::

# Materials and Methods

Acoustic data were collected using autonomous underwater recorders (SoundTrap 300 HF) 
deployed at depths of 20-30 meters. Recordings were made at a sampling 
rate of 48 kHz with a 16-bit resolution.

Song analysis was performed by visually inspecting spectrograms for 
repeated themes and phrases.

::endsection


::section{#results}
::meta
type: results
summary: "Comparison of song parameters between different South Pacific populations."
depends_on: ["#methods"]
::

# Results

A total of 450 song units were analyzed across three regions: Australia (East), 
Fiji, and French Polynesia.

::chart{#tbl-whale-stats}
::title Descriptive statistics of humpback whale song parameters
::interpretation
The data shows that the Australia population has significantly higher 
maximum frequencies compared to the French Polynesia population. Duration 
of themes is relatively consistent across all regions, averaging around 35 seconds.
::
| Population       | Min Freq (Hz) | Max Freq (Hz) | Phrase Duration (s) | No. Themes |
|------------------|---------------|---------------|---------------------|------------|
| Australia (East) | 120           | 4,500         | 8.2                 | 6          |
| Fiji             | 145           | 3,800         | 7.8                 | 5          |
| French Polynesia | 110           | 3,200         | 9.1                 | 7          |
::endchart

::diagram{#fig-song-structure}
::type flowchart
::description
This diagram shows the hierarchical structure of a humpback whale song, from 
individual units to phrases, themes, and finally the complete song cycle.
::
```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Unit] --> B[Phrase]
    B --> C[Theme]
    C --> D[Song Cycle]
```
::enddiagram

::endsection


::section{#conclusion}
::meta
type: conclusion
summary: "Implications of the observed acoustic variation for population connectivity."
depends_on: ["#results"]
::

# Conclusion

The observed acoustic divergence between western and eastern populations 
suggests that while cultural transmission is a powerful driver of song 
change, geographical barriers continue to influence acoustic repertoire 
diversity in the South Pacific.

::endsection
